July 29, 2019

Introduction

  • Predicting metabolic state from standardized scatter intensities
  • Comparing linear methods to non-linear methods for the task

Support Vector Machines with Radial Kernel

  • non-probabilistic
  • maximises the margin

\[ \begin{array}{l}{\underset{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}{\operatorname{argmax}} \sum_{n} \alpha_{n}-\frac{1}{2} \sum_{n, m} \alpha_{n} \alpha_{m} y_{n} y_{m} \mathbf{x}_{n}^{\top} \mathbf{x}_{m}} \\ {\text { with constraint: } \sum_{n=1}^{N} \alpha_{n} y_{n}=0, \quad 0 \leq \alpha_{n} \leq C} \end{array} \]

What if there is no linear hyperplane that separates the data?

\[ \underset{\boldsymbol{\alpha}}{\operatorname{argmax}} \sum_{n} \alpha_{n}-\frac{1}{2} \sum_{n, m} \alpha_{n} \alpha_{m} y_{n} y_{m} K\left(\mathbf{x}_{n}, \mathbf{x}_{m}\right) \]

Kernels:

  • Polynomial
  • Radial: \(K\left(\mathbf{x}_{n}, \mathbf{x}_{m}\right)=\exp \left\{-\gamma\left(\mathbf{x}_{n}-\mathbf{x}_{m}\right)^{\top}\left(\mathbf{x}_{n}-\mathbf{x}_{m}\right)\right\}\), where \(\gamma\) is a hyperparameter which controls the complexity of the decision boundary

GLMs for Logistic Regression

  • a systematic component, the linear combination of predictors and parameters \(\mathbf \theta^\top x\)
  • a random component, which defines the distributions of the outcomes
  • a link function, so that \(\mathbb{E}(Y) = g^{-1}(\mathbf \theta^\top x).\)

Regularized Logistic Regression

\[ \mathrm{h}_{\theta}(x) = P(Y=1 | \mathbf{x} ; \theta) =g^{-1}\left(\theta^{T} \mathbf{x}\right)=\frac{1}{1+e^{-\theta^{T} \mathbf{x}}} \]

To find the parameters: \[ \min_{\theta}J(\theta)=-y \log \left(h_{\theta}(\mathbf{x})\right)-(1-y) \log \left(1-h_{\theta}(\mathbf{x})\right) \]

For multiple classes: \[ P(Y=k | \mathbf{x} ; \theta)=\frac{e^{-\theta_{k}^{T} \mathbf{x}}}{\sum_{k=1}^{K} e^{-\theta^{T} \mathbf{x}}} \]

Elastic Net

Elastic net penalized the regression coefficients based on both the \(L_1\) norm and the \(L_2\) norm: \[\min_{\theta}J(\theta) +\lambda_{1} \sum_{j=1}^{n_{P}}\left|\theta_{j}\right|+\lambda_{2} \sum_{j=1}^{n_{P}} \theta_{j}^{2}\]

\(L_1\) (LASSO):

  • Sparsity
  • Only one amongst many correlated variables is selected

\(L_2\) (Ridge):

  • Grouped selection
  • It works well with multicollinear variables

Nested Cross-validation

Models depend on hyperparameter choice to trade off the misclassification error against cost minimization.

To compare models, the resampling strategy MUST be the same.

Kappa

Accuracy can be problematic when the classes are unbalanced. Accuracy is threshold dependent.

\[ \text{Kappa}=\frac{\text {Total Accuracy}-\text {Random Accuracy}}{1-\text {Random Accuracy}} \]

Pros:

  • Normalized so we can compare performance of two algorithms on the same classification task
  • Tables can give an approximate idea of how well a value of Kappa is

Cons:

  • Threshold dependent just like accuracy



Ideal to use Brier score but resource intensive

Hypothesis Testing

  • Parametric requires assumption of normality
  • Non-parametric does not allow us to reject \(H_0\), but have little power
  • Bayesian hierarchical modelling

Summary

  • Data: Raman shift and intensities + one categorical variable
  • Goal: Compare linear methods with non-linear methods for this task
  • Algorithms: Regularized logistic regression (linear) and Radial Support Vector Machines (non-linear)
  • Resampling: Nested Cross-validation
  • Metric: Kappa
  • Hypothesis testing: Bayesian approach
  • Results: GLM better on Chlorella and worse on Rhodo

Advanced

  • Pre-processing data with PCA before Logistic Regression
  • Improving SVM by trying other kernels
  • Random Forest (probabilistic)

Additional: Bayesian approach

\[ \begin{array}{l}{\mathbf{\delta_{i}} \sim M V N\left(\mathbf{1} \mu_{i}, \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{i}}\right)} \\{\mu_{1}, \mu_{2} \sim t\left(\mu_{0}, \sigma_{0}, \nu\right)} \\ {\sigma_{1}, \sigma_{2} \sim \operatorname{unif}(0, 1000\overline{s})} \end{array}, \] where \(\overline{s}\) is the standard deviation of the \(\delta_i\)s averaged on different data sets.

\[\begin{array}{l}{\mu_{0} \sim \operatorname{unif}(-1,1)} \\ {\sigma_{0} \sim \operatorname{unif}\left(0, 1000s_{\overline{\delta}}\right)} \\ {\nu \sim \operatorname{Gamma}(\alpha, \beta)} \\ {\alpha \sim \operatorname{unif}(0.5, 5)} \\ {\beta \sim \operatorname{unif}(0.05,0.15)}\end{array},\] where \(s_{\overline{\delta}}\) is the standard deviation of the \(\delta_i\)s from one data set.

We define a region of practical equivalence (rope): (-0.01,0.01) We sample from the posterior distribution of \(\delta_i\) on both data sets. We record the number of times that \(\delta_\text{new}\) is smaller or greater than the rope. We calculate probabilities.

Advantage: \(\delta_i\)s in one data set borrow strength from the \(\delta_i\)s of another data set.
